ailures to address the compounding effects of generations of disinvestment. Police violence, mass incarceration of Black people, employment and housing discrimination, economic deprivation, and gross inequities in health care combine to deeply embed racial inequality in American society and economy. Updated to include the most recent evidence, including contemporary research on the racially disparate effects of the Covid-19 pandemic, this edition of Whitewashing Race analyzes the consequential and ongoing legacy of ";disaccumulation"; for Black communities and lives. While some progress has been made, the authors argue that real racial justice can be achieved only if we actively attack and undo pervasive structural racism and its legacies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Race & Ethnic Relations.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aafrican americans.  aamerica.  aamerican culture.  aamerican society.  abigotry.  ablack americans.  acolor blindness.  acriminal justice system.  acriminologists.  acultural criticism.  aeconomists.  ahealth care discrimination.  ahistorians.  ahousing discrimination.  alegal scholars.  alow income families.  aneo conservatives.  apolitical scientists.  aracial discrimination.  aracial inequality.  aracial issues.  aracial prejudice.  asociologists.  aunited states.  awage gaps.  awelfare state.  awhite americans.  awhitewashing.1 aCarnoy, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCurrie, Elliott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOppenheimer, David B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052039460540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520394605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520394605/o